# Django Model Naming Convention

All database tables and columns MUST use snake_case naming.

## Table Names

Every model MUST have an explicit `db_table` in its `Meta` class using plural snake_case:

```python
# ✅ GOOD
class FormTemplate(models.Model):
    class Meta:
        db_table = 'form_templates'

class FormTemplateField(models.Model):
    class Meta:
        db_table = 'form_template_fields'

# ❌ BAD — missing db_table, Django auto-generates "appname_formtemplate"
class FormTemplate(models.Model):
    class Meta:
        ordering = ['name']
```

## Column Names

All field names MUST be snake_case. Django uses the field name as the column name by default:

```python
# ✅ GOOD
first_name = models.CharField(max_length=100)
is_required = models.BooleanField(default=False)
created_at = models.DateTimeField(auto_now_add=True)

# ❌ BAD
firstName = models.CharField(max_length=100)
isRequired = models.BooleanField(default=False)
```

## Current Convention Reference

| Model | db_table |
|-------|----------|
| Contact | `contacts` |
| ContactNumber | `contact_numbers` |
| ContactAddress | `contact_addresses` |
| Document | `documents` |
| EmailLog | `email_logs` |
| FormTemplate | `form_templates` |
| FormTemplateField | `form_template_fields` |
| FormTemplateFieldOption | `form_template_field_options` |
| PasswordResetToken | `password_reset_tokens` |
